<n-docbody><doc bill="Y"><content.metadata.block><cmd.identifiers><cmd.cites><cmd.second.line.cite><bop/><bos/>Ga. Evidence § 3:3<eos/><eop/></cmd.second.line.cite></cmd.cites></cmd.identifiers></content.metadata.block><prop.block><prop.head toc-guid=""><bop/><bos/><headtext>Agnor&apos;s Georgia Evidence</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head><content.metadata.block><cmd.dates><cmd.currency.default iso.d="20191101"><bop/><bos/>November 2019 Update<eos/><eop/></cmd.currency.default></cmd.dates></content.metadata.block><author.line><bop/><bos/><author>Ana Marcela Rountree</author><eos/><eop/></author.line><prop.head toc-guid="I260dc1c0630a11eab5989292d3e01631"><bop/><bos/><label.name>Chapter</label.name><label.designator>3.</label.designator><headtext>Statutory Privileges</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head></prop.block><message.block><include.copyright n-include_collection="w_wlnv_msg" n-include_guid="I1DA35ED81DD211B281BAD200220BDFCA">Copr. (C) West 2005 No Claim to Orig. U.S. Govt. Works</include.copyright></message.block><section><section.front><doc.title toc-guid="Id71f2cc6682311ea83aee46e6decbb85"><head parent="doc.title"><bop/><bos/><label.name>§ </label.name><label.designator>3:3.</label.designator><headtext>Spousal privilege—Criminal cases</headtext><eos/><eop/></head></doc.title></section.front><section.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>The case of <cite.query w-src-number="0287018100" w-serial-number="1980105854" w-seq-number="00001" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000708" ID="Ia11a48f274d211eab2f0b920da2605c5"><ital>Trammel v. U.S.</ital></cite.query>,[<footnote.reference refid="I76f635b074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">1</footnote.reference>] which established the rule that a spouse may choose whether to testify against another in a criminal case was a departure from both proposed <cite.query w-src-number="0287018100" w-seq-number="00003" w-ref-type="ES" w-normalized-cite="USFRER505" w-pub-number="1000607" ID="Ia11c44c074d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">Fed. R. Evid. 505</cite.query> and historical federal precedent, both of which would have barred adverse testimony of one spouse absent the consent of both. <eos/><bos/><cite.query w-src-number="0287018100" w-seq-number="00004" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST24-5-503" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="Ia11c44c174d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">O.C.G.A. § 24-5-503</cite.query> carves out a special marital privilege recognized in criminal cases which is different from the privilege created in <cite.query w-src-number="0287018100" w-seq-number="00005" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST24-5-501" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="Ia11c44c274d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">O.C.G.A. § 24-5-501(a)(1)</cite.query> because it addresses the compellability of one spouse to become a witness for or against another in a criminal proceeding and not the admissibility of evidence.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="I76f635b174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">2</footnote.reference>] The statute provides that a <begin.quote ID="QT_0001"/><?page no="50"?>“[h]usband and wife … shall not be compellable to give evidence in any criminal proceeding for or against each other.”<eos/><bos/><end.quote refid="QT_0001"/>[<footnote.reference refid="I76f65cc074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">3</footnote.reference>] Thus, the spouse of a criminal defendant has a privilege not to testify for or against the defendant spouse in any criminal proceeding. <eos/><bos/>The privilege belongs to the witness spouse alone and cannot be claimed by the defendant spouse.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="I76f65cc174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">4</footnote.reference>] Likewise, only the witness spouse may waive the privilege.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>Waiver of the privilege need not be express. <eos/><bos/>The spouse waives any right to claim privilege under <cite.query w-src-number="0287018100" w-seq-number="00014" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST24-5-503" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="Ia11e409074d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">O.C.G.A. § 24-5-503</cite.query> when she voluntarily takes the stand, even if she does so as a defense witness.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="I76f683d174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">5</footnote.reference>] Under such circumstances, she will be subject to cross examination by the prosecution[<footnote.reference refid="I76f6aae074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">6</footnote.reference>] and the court is under no obligation to advise the witness of her right to claim privilege.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="I76f6aae274d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">7</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>Because the defendant cannot compel his spouse to testify, it is grounds for a mistrial if the district attorney comments on the failure of the defendant&apos;s wife to testify.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="I76f6d1f074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">8</footnote.reference>] It may also be reversible error to require the testifying spouse to claim the privilege within the hearing of the jury.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="I76f6d1f174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">9</footnote.reference>] The election of the spouse not to testify against the defendant should be made out of the presence of the jury.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="I76f6d1f274d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">10</footnote.reference><?page no="51"?>] However, it is not error if defense counsel could have avoided public invocation of the privilege by requesting that the matter be addressed outside the presence of the jury when the testifying spouse took the stand and was expected to claim privilege.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="I76f6f90074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">11</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>Unlike the spousal privilege recognized in <cite.query w-src-number="0287018100" w-seq-number="00030" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST24-5-501" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="Ia121c30074d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">O.C.G.A. § 24-5-501(a)(1)</cite.query>, the privilege recognized in <cite.query w-src-number="0287018100" w-seq-number="00031" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST24-5-503" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="Ia121c30174d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">O.C.G.A. § 24-5-503</cite.query> is not permanent and does <ital>not</ital> survive divorce or death of a spouse.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="I76f6f90174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">12</footnote.reference>] When a claim of privilege is made pursuant to this section, the witness must be lawfully married to the defendant at the time of the trial. <eos/><bos/>It is irrelevant when the communication was made or whether it was intended to be confidential.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>Because no other privilege sweeps as broadly, savvy criminal defendants have been known to marry a potential witness for the sole reason of gaining the benefits of the privilege at trial. <eos/><bos/>The Georgia Court of Appeals has held that the marital privilege provided by this section&apos;s predecessor, <cite.query w-src-number="0287018100" w-seq-number="00033" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST24-9-23" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="Ia122ad6074d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">O.C.G.A. § 24-9-23</cite.query>,[<footnote.reference refid="I76f7201074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">13</footnote.reference>] may be invoked regardless of any underlying motives for the marriage.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="I76f7201174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">14</footnote.reference>] The proponent of the privilege is only required to show that a valid, legal marriage exists.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>No marital privilege exists in cases in which the husband or wife is charged with a crime against a minor child[<footnote.reference refid="I76f7201274d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">15</footnote.reference>] or his or her spouse (pursuant to a lawful marriage).<eos/><bos/>[<footnote.reference refid="I76f7201374d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">16</footnote.reference>] In such cases, the privilege is waived only with respect to evidence on the specific act for which the defendant is charged.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="I76f7472074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">17</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para></section.body></section><footnote.block><footnote ID="I76f635b074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>1</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287018100" w-serial-number="1980105854" w-seq-number="00002" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000708" ID="Ia11a971274d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">Trammel v. U.S., 445 U.S. 40, 100 S. Ct. 906, 63, 63 L. Ed. 2d 186, 5 Fed. R. Evid. Serv. 737 (1980)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="I76f635b174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>2</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287018100" w-serial-number="1985154459" w-seq-number="00006" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Ia11c6bd274d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">Chadwick v. State, 176 Ga. App. 296, 335 S.E.2d 674 (1985)</cite.query><?page no="50"?>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="I76f65cc074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>3</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287018100" w-seq-number="00007" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST24-5-503" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="Ia11cb9f074d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">O.C.G.A. § 24-5-503</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="I76f65cc174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>4</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287018100" w-serial-number="1974128555" w-seq-number="00008" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Ia11d2f2274d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">Young v. State, 232 Ga. 285, 206 S.E.2d 439 (1974)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287018100" w-serial-number="1984105300" w-seq-number="00009" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Ia11d2f2574d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">Ballard v. State, 252 Ga. 53, 311 S.E.2d 453 (1984)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287018100" w-serial-number="1991100406" w-seq-number="00010" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Ia11d2f2874d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">Brown v. State, 199 Ga. App. 188, 404 S.E.2d 469 (1991)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287018100" w-serial-number="2002294923" w-seq-number="00011" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Ia11d2f2b74d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">Biswas v. State, 255 Ga. App. 339, 565 S.E.2d 531 (2002)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>However, the defendant spouse does still have a right to claim privilege with respect to any confidential communications. <eos/><bos/>See <cite.query w-src-number="0287018100" w-seq-number="00012" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST24-5-501" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="Ia11dcb6074d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">O.C.G.A. § 24-5-501</cite.query>; <cite.query w-ref-type="DA" w-normalized-cite="GAEVIDENCES3:2" w-pub-number="160247" ID="I76f683d074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">§ 3:2</cite.query>, <cite.query w-src-number="0287018100" w-serial-number="2002294923" w-seq-number="00013" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000360" ID="Ia11dcb6174d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">supra.</cite.query></paratext><eos/><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="I76f683d174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>5</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287018100" w-serial-number="1994055307" w-seq-number="00015" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Ia11e67a274d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">White v. State, 211 Ga. App. 694, 440 S.E.2d 68 (1994)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287018100" w-serial-number="2002294923" w-seq-number="00016" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Ia11e67a574d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">Biswas v. State, 255 Ga. App. 339, 565 S.E.2d 531 (2002)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="I76f6aae074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>6</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>See <cite.query w-src-number="0287018100" w-serial-number="1994055307" w-seq-number="00017" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Ia11f2af274d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">White v. State, 211 Ga. App. 694, 440 S.E.2d 68 (1994)</cite.query>, holding that the testifying wife waived privilege when she voluntarily took the stand as defense witness and was subject to a thorough cross-examination. <eos/><bos/>However, this has no effect on the marital privilege recognized in <cite.query w-src-number="0287018100" w-seq-number="00018" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST24-5-501" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="Ia11f2af374d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">O.C.G.A. § 24-5-501(a)(1)</cite.query> under which the spouse would still be entitled to claim privilege of confidential marital communications, if applicable. <eos/><bos/>See <cite.query w-src-number="0287018100" w-seq-number="00019" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST24-5-501" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="Ia11f2af474d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">O.C.G.A. § 24-5-501</cite.query> and <cite.query w-ref-type="DA" w-normalized-cite="GAEVIDENCES3:2" w-pub-number="160247" ID="I76f6aae174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">§ 3:2</cite.query>, <cite.query w-src-number="0287018100" w-serial-number="1994055307" w-seq-number="00020" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000360" ID="Ia11f2af574d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">supra.</cite.query></paratext><eos/><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="I76f6aae274d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>7</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287018100" w-serial-number="1979128344" w-seq-number="00021" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Ia11f791274d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">Wiley v. State, 150 Ga. App. 607, 258 S.E.2d 286 (1979)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287018100" w-serial-number="1989126536" w-seq-number="00022" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Ia11f791574d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">Mapp v. State, 191 Ga. App. 622, 382 S.E.2d 618 (1989)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="I76f6d1f074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>8</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287018100" w-serial-number="1982107878" w-seq-number="00023" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000849" ID="Ia120155374d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">Ferry v. State, 161 Ga. App. 795, 287 S.E.2d 732, 26 A.L.R.4th 1 (1982)</cite.query> (district attorney&apos;s comment on the failure of the defendant&apos;s wife to testify was grounds for a mistrial in the absence of any curative action by the trial court).<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="I76f6d1f174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>9</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287018100" w-serial-number="1985148585" w-seq-number="00024" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Ia1208a8274d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">Price v. State, 175 Ga. App. 780, 334 S.E.2d 711 (1985)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287018100" w-serial-number="1983151865" w-seq-number="00025" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Ia1208a8574d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">Wynn v. State, 168 Ga. App. 132, 308 S.E.2d 392 (1983)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287018100" w-serial-number="1982117938" w-seq-number="00026" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Ia1208a8874d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">Westbrook v. State, 162 Ga. App. 130, 290 S.E.2d 333 (1982)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287018100" w-serial-number="1976144251" w-seq-number="00027" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Ia1208a8b74d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">Colson v. State, 138 Ga. App. 366, 226 S.E.2d 154 (1976)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="I76f6d1f274d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>10</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287018100" w-serial-number="1982117938" w-seq-number="00028" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Ia120ffb274d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">Westbrook v. State, 162 Ga. App. 130, 290 S.E.2d 333 (1982)</cite.query><?page no="51"?>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="I76f6f90074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>11</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287018100" w-serial-number="1992069296" w-seq-number="00029" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Ia12174e274d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">Patterson v. State, 202 Ga. App. 440, 414 S.E.2d 895 (1992)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="I76f6f90174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>12</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287018100" w-serial-number="1985154459" w-seq-number="00032" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Ia121ea1274d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">Chadwick v. State, 176 Ga. App. 296, 335 S.E.2d 674 (1985)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="I76f7201074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>13</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>Repealed effective January 1, 2013.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="I76f7201174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>14</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287018100" w-serial-number="1994140370" w-seq-number="00034" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Ia122fb8274d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">State v. Peters, 213 Ga. App. 352, 444 S.E.2d 609 (1994)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="I76f7201274d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>15</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>See <cite.query w-src-number="0287018100" w-seq-number="00035" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST24-5-503" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="Ia12397c074d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">O.C.G.A. § 24-5-503(b)(1)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="I76f7201374d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>16</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287018100" w-seq-number="00036" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST24-5-503" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="Ia123bed074d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">O.C.G.A. § 24-5-503(b)(2)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="I76f7472074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>17</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287018100" w-seq-number="00037" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST24-5-503" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="Ia1240cf074d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">O.C.G.A. § 24-5-503(b)(1)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote></footnote.block><content.metadata.block><cmd.royalty><cmd.copyright><bop/><bos/>Westlaw. © 2019 Thomson Reuters.  <eos/><bos/>No Claim to Orig. U.S. Govt. <eos/><bos/>Works.<eos/><eop/></cmd.copyright></cmd.royalty><cmd.identifiers><cmd.cites><cmd.first.line.cite><bop/><bos/>GAEVIDENCE § 3:3<eos/><eop/></cmd.first.line.cite></cmd.cites></cmd.identifiers></content.metadata.block></doc></n-docbody>
